ore, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Tibbermore, Perthshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland":"Ruthven, Perthshire, Schotland","Ruthven Castle, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Ruthven Castle, Perthshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ruthven Castle, Perthshire, Scotland":"Ruthven Castle, Perthshire, Schotland"},"en":{"1165–1240":"1165–1240","1180–1204":"1180–1204","1180–Male":"1180–Deceased","1188–Male":"1188–Deceased","–1272":"–1272","1210–1250":"1210–1250","1138–1199":"1138–1199","1140–Female":"1140–Deceased","1204":"1204","1138":"1138","1199":"1199","1210":"1210","1188":"1188","1165":"1165","1240":"1240","1140":"1140","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1180":"1180","Tibbermore, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Tibbermore, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland":"Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland","Ruthven Castle, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Ruthven Castle, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Ruthven Castle, Perthshire, Scotland":"Ruthven Castle, Perthshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ruthven,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name, traditionally pronounced ‘Ri-ven’, from Ruthven by Huntingtower (Perthshire); also possibly from Ruthven (Angus) and various other places of that name throughout Scotland, named either with Gaelic <i>ruadh</i> ‘red’ + <i>mhaighin</i> ‘place’ or with a cognate of Welsh <i>rhudd faen</i> ‘red stone’. The oldest family of this name, the lords of the barony of Ruthven by Perth, were descended from Thor, son of Swain, lord of Tranent in Lothian and first sheriff of Edinburgh on record in the mid 12th century. The family eventually gained the title of Earl of Gowrie, but because of what became known as ‘the Gowrie Conspiracy’ the title was forfeited and from 1600 to 1641 the surname itself was proscribed. The title was later restored to the family, and the present Earl of Gowrie bears the surname <i>Ruthven</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Alan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alan Ruthven, 1st Lord of Ruthven was born in 1165, in Ruthven Castle, Perthshire, Scotland, his father, Swein Son of Thor, was 27 and his mother, Mrs. Elizabeth Ruthven, was 25. He had at least 1 son with Cecilia De Maule. He died in 1240, in Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland, at the age of 75."},"et":{"1165–1240":"1165–1240","1180–1204":"1180–1204","1180–Male":"1180–Surnud","1188–Male":"1188–Surnud","–1272":"–1272","1210–1250":"1210–1250","1138–1199":"1138–1199","1140–Female":"1140–Surnud","1204":"1204","1138":"1138","1199":"1199","1210":"1210","1188":"1188","1165":"1165","1240":"1240","1140":"1140","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1180":"1180","Tibbermore, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Tibbermore, Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland":"Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland","Ruthven Castle, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Ruthven Castle, Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Ruthven Castle, Perthshire, Scotland":"Ruthven Castle, Perthshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1165–1240":"1165–1240","1180–1204":"1180–1204","1180–Male":"1180–Kuollut","1188–Male":"1188–Kuollut","–1272":"–1272","1210–1250":"1210–1250","1138–1199":"1138–1199","1140–Female":"1140–Kuollut","